## 3. System Architecture

The project employs a robust **Modular Client-Side Architecture** divided into three distinct layers. This separation of concerns ensures code maintainability and scalability.

```mermaid
graph TD
    subgraph UI Layer [UI Layer (HTML & Bootstrap)]
        A[Views & Pages]
        B[Shared Components]
        C[Toast Notifications]
    end

    subgraph Logic Layer [Business Logic (JavaScript Modules)]
        D[main.js]
        E[auth.js]
        F[books.js]
        G[exchange.js]
        H[admin.js]
        I[ui.js]
    end

    subgraph Storage Layer [Data Layer (LocalStorage Wrapper)]
        J[database.js]
    end

    A <--> D
    B <--> I
    
    D --> E
    D --> F
    D --> G
    D --> H
    
    E <--> J
    F <--> J
    G <--> J
    H <--> J
```

### Architecture Layers Explained:

*   **UI Layer (Presentation):** Responsible for rendering the interfaces. It utilizes Bootstrap 5 for responsiveness and styling, alongside custom CSS variables ensuring a consistent theme (including Dark Mode).
*   **Business Logic Layer:** The JavaScript modules mediate between the UI and the data. Each module ([auth.js](file:///f:/college%20projects/BOOKEXCHANGESYSTEM/js/auth.js), [books.js](file:///f:/college%20projects/BOOKEXCHANGESYSTEM/js/books.js), etc.) handles specific domain logic, enforcing rules like route protection and search algorithms.
*   **Storage Layer ([database.js](file:///f:/college%20projects/BOOKEXCHANGESYSTEM/js/database.js)):** A wrapper utility that abstracts raw `LocalStorage` calls. It serializes and deserializes JSON data, manages unique IDs, and provides unified CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) methods for the rest of the application.

